Preheat the #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Pour @cold salted water{300%ml} into a #medium pot{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}.

Stir in the @rice{150%g} and bring to the boil.

Once boiling, lower the heat to medium, cover, and cook for ~{10%mins}.

Remove from the heat. Keep covered for ~{10%mins} or until ready to serve (the
rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Halve the @bell pepper{1}(halved and sliced into thin strips) and discard the
core and seeds.

Trim and thinly slice the @scallion{1}(trimmed and thinly sliced).

Place a #pan{} over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once hot, fry the @Irish beef mince{240%g} with the pepper until browned,
~{5-6%mins}. IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw mince. Mince
is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Use a #spoon{} to break up the beef as it cooks. Season with @salt{to taste}
and @pepper{to taste}.

Add the @North Indian style spice mix{1%sachet} and @garam masala{1%sachet} and
cook until fragrant, stirring continuously, ~{1%min}.

Add the @chopped tomato with onion & garlic{1%pack}, @beef stock{1%sachet} and
@cranberry chutney{1%sachet} to the beef.

Cover and simmer for ~{5-6%mins}.

Add a splash of @water{to taste} if you feel the mince has become too dry.

Season to taste with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Once cooked, remove from the heat and stir through a knob of @butter{to taste}.

Meanwhile, place @naan{2} onto a #baking tray{} and sprinkle with a little
water.

Pop into the oven to warm through, ~{2-3%mins}.

Divide the spiced beef between plates.

Serve with the rice and warm naan alongside.

Top with a sprinkling of scallion.